putting ideas into action.

00:38:49.450 --> 00:38:52.760
JOHN WERNER: So that's
the talk that didn't

00:38:52.760 --> 00:38:54.844
happen at my kid's school.

00:38:54.844 --> 00:38:56.510
But what that made
me realize is there's

00:38:56.510 --> 00:38:57.890
people with social capital.

00:38:57.890 --> 00:39:00.210
Steve Vinter has
ridiculous social capital.

00:39:00.210 --> 00:39:03.350
People walk around
the Earth for him.

00:39:03.350 --> 00:39:05.600
You can't just plug that
social capital into schools

00:39:05.600 --> 00:39:08.130
as schools exist-- Columbine,
other safety issues.

00:39:08.130 --> 00:39:11.390
But if we created a mechanism
to kind of connect people.

00:39:11.390 --> 00:39:16.340
So the top 2% or 10%
of Wikipedia generators

00:39:16.340 --> 00:39:17.890
do most of the generation.

00:39:17.890 --> 00:39:21.990
What if we unleashed content
generation of these Adventures

00:39:21.990 --> 00:39:25.300
to the masses, and all
that content went out

00:39:25.300 --> 00:39:27.570
on different social avenues?

00:39:27.570 --> 00:39:29.695
Now right now, if you want
to go to the Super Bowl,

00:39:29.695 --> 00:39:31.870
it's pretty expensive.

00:39:31.870 --> 00:39:33.650
You have to pay a lot of money.

00:39:33.650 --> 00:39:36.530
But what if we
disrupted tickets,

00:39:36.530 --> 00:39:39.620
and suddenly every
institution-- art houses,

00:39:39.620 --> 00:39:42.920
historic places-- set aside a
certain percentage of tickets,

00:39:42.920 --> 00:39:45.470
because they wanted to curate
a more interesting audience

00:39:45.470 --> 00:39:47.969
through Adventures than they
thought they could get randomly

00:39:47.969 --> 00:39:49.140
by people buying tickets?

00:39:49.140 --> 00:39:52.700
And if they got a little bit
of access, some social media,

00:39:52.700 --> 00:39:55.640
some new selfies were
created that would

00:39:55.640 --> 00:39:57.390
be more valuable than
nickel and diming

00:39:57.390 --> 00:40:01.910
people for the $1,200 per
ticket, that's a big idea.

00:40:01.910 --> 00:40:04.360
The other thing is
I was at Google I/O.

00:40:04.360 --> 00:40:06.070
And I took five of these.

00:40:06.070 --> 00:40:08.600
I really like your Oculus Rift.

00:40:08.600 --> 00:40:12.006
There's a lot of content that
needs to be generated for VR.

00:40:12.006 --> 00:40:13.380
And there are
going to be drones.

00:40:13.380 --> 00:40:14.879
And Google Street
View, you're going

00:40:14.879 --> 00:40:16.460
to have cars driving around.

00:40:16.460 --> 00:40:18.910
But what if you created
a format, a standard,

00:40:18.910 --> 00:40:21.370
through these Adventures,
if you went fractal,

00:40:21.370 --> 00:40:22.930
and tens and
thousands and millions

00:40:22.930 --> 00:40:25.860
and kajillions and
kabillions of content

00:40:25.860 --> 00:40:27.240
was generated that
suddenly could

00:40:27.240 --> 00:40:31.110
become the future of
the VR experience?

00:40:31.110 --> 00:40:34.930
So I think we can flip some
traditional institutions--

00:40:34.930 --> 00:40:36.550
education, journalism.

00:40:36.550 --> 00:40:40.150
At a time when we need
journalism more than ever,

00:40:40.150 --> 00:40:45.310
editorializing how
complicated life is-- cloning,

00:40:45.310 --> 00:40:47.920
climate change, all these
things-- the business model

00:40:47.920 --> 00:40:49.190
dropped out.

00:40:49.190 --> 00:40:50.550
Talk to Chris.

00:40:50.550 --> 00:40:53.010
Every quarter, he had to
let go of half his staff.

00:40:53.010 --> 00:40:54.490
Because people
aren't buying ads.

00:40:54.490 --> 00:40:56.300
Because Google,
you're killing it.

00:40:56.300 --> 00:40:58.050
But what if we created
these Adventures

00:40:58.050 --> 00:41:02.380
as a new form of journalism
or education or conferences?

